Scribonia was divorced upon the same day, having lost the one strong claim she might have possessed to the Emperor's gratitude.1 But Virgil’s Eclogue had been already published, and was itself, as an ante-natal ode must always be, more concerned with the father than the child, more indeed with the hopes ol the world than with either father or child.
